<HL> Ride Urges NASA
To Examine Earth
And Explore Mars
---
By Laurie McGinley
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 08/18/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> GOVMT
AEROSPACE (ARO) </IN>
<DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Astronaut Sally Ride, warning that the U.S. has relinquished its leadership in space in crucial areas, urged a detailed examination of the Earth from orbit and the human exploration of Mars early in the next century. 

   Ms. Ride's long-awaited report represents the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's latest effort to get the beleaguered U.S. space program back on track following last year's Challenger accident. 
The space shuttle catastrophe made NASA's "shortcomings starkly apparent," said Ms. Ride, who will leave the space agency next month to take a post at a California think tank. 

   The report to James Fletcher, administrator of NASA, said that while the U.S. pioneered exploration of Mars using unmanned spacecraft, no American spacecraft has visited the planet since 1976. 
By contrast, the Soviets have announced an extensive exploration program using robots. 

   The U.S. also is far behind the Soviets in inhabiting "low-earth orbit" space stations; while the U.S. hasn't had a space station since Skylab was vacated in 1974, the Soviets have had eight space stations in orbit since the mid-1970s, the report said. 

   In mapping a blueprint for the revitalization of the U.S. space effort, Ms. Ride studied four options: 

   --"Mission to Planet Earth," which would use satellites in low-earth orbit, an orbit as far as 350 miles from the Earth, to examine the earth's atmosphere, ocean topography and vegetation. 

   --Exploration of the solar system, which would send unmanned spacecraft to a comet, Saturn and Mars for detailed study. 

   --"Moon Output," which would call for a return to the moon by the year 2000, leading eventually to a permanent lunar base for research and observation. 

   --"Humans to Mars," which would aim at landing Americans on Mars early in the 21st century. 

   Ms. Ride, in evaluating the options, didn't give the space agency explicit advice on how to proceed. 
But she did suggest that the most constructive strategy would be to focus initially on the Earth-observation program, while making plans to return to the moon and eventually to visit Mars. 
At the same time, she urged the agency to "solidly support" unmanned planetary exploration through the next decade. 

   Ms. Ride didn't provide cost estimates, but said such programs will have to stay within the fiscal constraints that NASA will face in coming years. 

   While acknowledging that exploring and settling Mars "should be the ultimate objectives of human exploration," Ms. Ride warned against a "rush headlong toward Mars." 
She added, "We should adopt a strategy to continue an orderly expansion outward from the earth." 

   Ms. Ride's report may displease those who have urged NASA to adopt, with great fanfare, the human inhabitation of Mars as the space agency's next big goal. 
Some believe that only such a glamorous, high-profile project can recapture the public's interest in the space program. 

   But others have argued that the space agency should follow a more gradual approach to future exploration. 
In her report, Ms. Ride seemed to endorse the latter by calling for "a strategy of evolution and natural progression." 

</TEXT>
