<DESCRIPT>  SPACE; RESEARCH; PROGRAM; US; FACILITY; MOUNTAIN-VIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The next stop on our tour of Mars National Park is a vista point overlooking
the red-rock canyons of Valles Marineris, an awesome fissure that makes Planet
Earth's Grand Canyon look like a golf divot.;    Looking down from the Martian
ridge where we're standing, Valles Marineris is as deep as Mount Everest is
high. To the left, the 3,000-mile-long canyon stretches to the horizon. Behind
us are rocky side canyons.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  NASA BRINGS MARTIAN LANDSCAPE TO LIFE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Our guides to Mars' rugged terrain are a pair of visionary engineers at the
NASA/Ames Research Center in Mountain View with a "virtual reality" system
that takes users to the red planet.;    At least, almost. Virtual reality is,
as the engineers say, a metaphor.;    "You can put on goggles and feel what
it's like to be there," said Michael McGreevy, 41, the principal engineer in
the Human Interface Research Branch at the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration's Ames facility. "Is it as good as really going there? Hell,
no. But it's better than not going at all.";    Unlike flat computer screens,
virtual reality presents information in the way humans are used to getting it
-- interactively and all around them. As a sensor tracks head and hand
movements, a computer adjusts the scene on miniature computer screens mounted
in goggles that resemble scuba masks.;    "When you put on the head-mounted
display, you get the impression the panorama is wrapped around in space, just
as if you were really there in a three-dimensional world," said Lewis
Hitchner, McGreevy's partner.;    American researchers are developing
applications ranging from virtual walk-throughs of architectural plans to the
design of new planes to video games and simulated sex. In Japan, where virtual
reality is known as "tele-existence," a government-industry partnership is
exploring the technology for super-teleconferencing.;    McGreevy and Hitchner
want to use virtual reality to democratize planetary exploration. If they get
their way, the half-dozen adventurous astronauts chosen to blast off for Mars
will be accompanied by hundreds of geologists able to wander around Mars in a
"virtual environment.";    McGreevy, who has led the research team with a
shoestring budget since 1984, hopes his project will be included in next
year's Mars Observer mission. The orbiting spacecraft, which will take about
nine months to get to Mars, will use lasers to map every meter of the surface
of the planet. Feeding the data into a virtual reality system could give
researchers their first chance to "explore" the whole planet in detail.;   
Robots as camera carriers;  Ultimately, McGreevy dreams of a room-size virtual
reality facility in which scientists at Mission Control or at a manned Mars
base could personally interact with the terrain through robotic rovers
equipped with cameras, mechanical arms and other devices.;    Wearing goggles
and wired with sensors, geologists would wander around the virtual environment
looking under virtual outcroppings and picking up virtual rock samples in the
same way they would conduct field research on Earth. Their activities would
send signals to the rover, which would carry out the tasks on Mars.;    That
would be a huge advance over McGreevy's first virtual environment. As a
16-year-old on vacation in Paris, he snapped photographs of the Eiffel Tower.
At home, he pasted the pictures to the inside of a sphere and put his head
inside.;    Wraparound photos;  "Suddenly, I had this overwhelming feeling
that I was there," he said.;    Now, McGreevy and Hitchner can pick any
coordinate on Mars and load it up for exploration in less than 20 minutes. Of
course their simulation is only as accurate as the available data, which at
present are plot-points spaced one kilometer apart, gathered by the 1972
Mariner 9 expedition.;    That's enough for breathtaking stationary views from
vista points such as the one overlooking Valles Marineris, named after the
expedition that discovered it, and for less-detailed views while "flying.";   
"Would I like to get out and hike?" McGreevy said. "Sure. We're working on it."  </TEXT>
