<HL> Mars Moon Probe To Lift Off Today From Russian Site --- More Than a Dozen Nations Participating in Project; Remote Study of Planet </HL>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> FREST </CO>
<IN> ARO </IN>
<DATELINE> MOSCOW (AP)  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Space officials from more than a dozen countries converged on a Central Asian steppe yesterday for the launching of the first of two probes to Phobos, the potato-shaped moon of Mars. 

   The Soviet Union says the mission will help prepare for manned flight to the planet. 

   Soviet media said final preparations were being made at the Baikonur launch site in Kazakhstan for the liftoff today of Phobos I, a joint East-West project to study Phobos and Mars itself. 
Phobos II, the second satellite, is scheduled to be launched Tuesday. 

   Soviet television this week showed the silver-white Phobos I and its 60-yard-tall Soviet-made Proton rocket being moved into place. 

   The satellites will enter Mars's gravity in January and begin a three-month remote study of the surface and atmosphere of the planet. 
After that, scientists said, they will draw closer to Phobos and drop descent vehicles carrying laser, ionic and radar equipment to help determine the internal structure and composition of the moon. 
The probes are expected to be sent to Phobos in about April of next year, according to Roald Sagdeyev, director of the Soviet Academy of Sciences' Space Research Institute. 

   Soviet space scientists said Phobos is an important step toward a manned flight to Mars, which they hope can take place in the early 21st century. 
Officials including Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev have proposed that the U.S. take part in the mission. 

   "First, it is necessary to draw up a more accurate map of the Mars surface in order to choose a place for the future landing," said Vyacheslav Balebanov, a deputy to Mr. Sagdeyev. 

   "Then, it is necessary to study the climate and soil characteristics and find out whether oxygen should be taken from Earth, or whether it can be gotten directly on the planet. 
The study of Mars renewed under the Phobos program should provide answers to those questions," he said in an interview with the newspaper Sovietskaya Rossiya. 

   The Soviet news agency Tass said that the Phobos television system will provide color photographs and that a memory unit will permit transmission of up to 1,100 pictures to Earth. 

   Soviet space officials said the launching itself will cost about $65 million and that the total cost of the project was about $480 million. 

   Also participating in the project are Austria, Bulgaria, Hungary, East Germany, Ireland, Poland, Finland, France, West Germany, Czechoslovakia, Switzerland, Sweden, the U.S. and the European Space Agency. 
Many of those countries have provided equipment for experiments to be conducted by Phobos. 

   The U.S., a late entry into the Martian mission as relations have warmed with the Soviet Union, will be represented at the launching by a group headed by Lt. Gen. Donald Cromer, head of the Air Force space division, said U.S. Embassy spokeswoman Marguerite Squire. 

   The Deep Space Network of the U.S. National Aeronautics and Space Administration will provide tracking data to permit two 100-pound landers to reach Phobos, and then will begin to track the Martian moon precisely using antennas in California, Spain and Australia, and a Soviet radio telescope in the Crimea. 

   U.S. scientists say the Deep Space Network can determine distance within yards, and the velocity of spacecraft billons of miles from Earth. 

   Mr. Balebanov said scientists also suspect that Phobos is gradually drawing closer to Mars. 
The U.S. tracking may help to determine if that is true. 

   The Phobos craft will carry a plaque commemorating Phobos's discovery by a U.S. astronomer. 

   The probe is launched while the U.S. is still trying to recover from the loss of the space shuttle Challenger in 1986. 
Since then, the Soviet Union has had several space achievements, including the 326-day mission of cosmonaut Yuri Romanenko aboard the Mir orbiting space station. 

   The Soviet Union first sent a satellite toward Mars in 1962. 
The Mars-1 craft was the first of about 15 Soviet and U.S. probes that gathered a large amount of data from the planet, but not enough to determine the feasibility of a manned mission, Soviet scientists say. 

   Phobos "is a logical development of the Soviet program of Mars exploration that was started about a quarter of a century ago," cosmonaut Alexei Leonov told Tass. 

</TEXT>
