<HEAD>NASA Urged To Strengthen Life Sciences Program for Future Missions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA may have to conduct extensive
psychological testing, including some experiments that could last
years, before it can select crews for deep space flights such as a
voyage to Mars, an advisory panel said Wednesday.
   In a study of NASA's future needs for space exploration, the
panel said the agency will have to conduct extensive test programs
and develop new criteria for the selection of astronauts.
   The study, ``Exploring the Living Universe,'' outlines in broad
terms the changes the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
must make in order to be ready to staff a space station in Earth
orbit for months at a time, or to develop the equipment and
personnel for exploration beyond Earth orbit.
   ``Life sciences as it has been is inadequate to support the
goals of NASA,'' said Frederick C. Robbins, a Nobel laureate who
was chairman of the study committee.
   Robbins said the space agency must strengthen research areas not
only to learn how to send humans into space for long periods of
time, but also to explore the universe for possible life forms and
to study the planet central to the human species _ the Earth.
   He said the studies should gather more knowledge about the
effect of mankind on the Earth's environment because ``the threat
to our environment is real and is becoming more important to us all
the time. I would suggest that this (research) might provide a
mechanism for our continued existence on this planet.''
   Robbins said NASA will have to gain significantly more knowledge
about the effects of weightlessness and forced confinement on the
human body before the agency can hope to attempt long-term space
flight aboard the space station or to attempt a voyage to Mars.
   U.S. experience in long-term space flight is limited to the 84
days of Skylab 3, and this is not enough data to commit to missions
lasting years, such as a voyage to Mars, Robbins said.
   He said the Soviet cosmonaut Yuri Romanenko holds the world
space record of 326 days, but the Soviet Union has yet to share the
specific phsysiological data collected on that mission.
   The weightlessness of space causes muscles to atrophy, bones to
lose minerals and become thinner, and the cardiovascular system to
decondition. This reaction, called the space adaptation syndrome,
must be understood thoroughly before long-term space flight is
possible.
   Gerald Carr, a former astronaut who commanded the 84-day Skylab
flight and who helped prepare the report, said NASA also must study
the psychological aspects of long-term space flight.
   Carr said the current astronaut selection methods are not
adequate for choosing crew members for flights that could last
years.
   ``NASA is going to have to conduct very long-term tests in
situations where the test crew knows it can't `king's X' and walk
away from it,'' Carr said. He said what is currently known about
the confinement for years of small group of people in hazardous
situations, such as space flight, is inadequate ``because nobody
has ever done a study.''
   Carr said that the criterion used for selecting astronauts in
the past must be changed because future astronauts will face
stresses far more complex than those known to the people of Apollo
and Skylab.
   William C. Schneider, a former NASA executive who headed the
Skylab program and who also was on the study committee, said it is
``quite likely'' that NASA will have to conduct tests that could
last 500 days to 600 days to determine the criteria for selecting
crew members for long-duration space flight.
   ``There simply is no other way to gather the data,'' he said.
   In other recommendations, the committee said NASA should:
   _Conduct an intensified program of orbital experiments on human
life support in space, including development of self-contained
systems that recirculate oxygen and water.
   _Increase studies on the effects of gravity and weightlessness
on Earth life forms, including plants.
   _Increase studies related to the possible existence of life
forms beyond the Earth and on issues related to the evolution of
life.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

