<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The U.S. should develop nuclear-powered
spaceships if it wants to send astronauts to Mars, a White
House panel on space exploration recommended.
   The group, headed by former Apollo astronaut Thomas
Stafford, recommended a series of technologies and proposed
missions to explore the moon with astronauts in about 2005,
and Mars about 10 years later. Vice President Dan Quayle, who
heads the National Space Council, had directed the panel to
search broadly for technology that could cut costs and
advance the pace of space exploration.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But the 27-member group, packed with veterans of the
Apollo manned flights to the moon, largely recommended
dusting off Apollo technology that the National Aeronautics
and Space Administration had shelved in the early 1970s when
lunar exploration was canceled. Along with nuclear
spaceships, the Stafford report recommended resurrecting
engine technology from the Saturn moon rockets and
Apollo-style capsules for astronauts to splash down in after
traveling to Mars.
   "Why are we using that old technology? Well it's good,
solid technology," said Max Faget, a panel member who
designed the Apollo capsules. NASA Administrator Richard
Truly said the report showed that "there's only a limited
number of ways to get to space."
   Using older technology could reduce costs somewhat from
the $500 billion exploration program NASA proposed in 1989,
said John Pike, a space analyst at the Federation of American
Scientists. The White House study recommended fewer vehicles
than the NASA proposal and also said it didn't need to use an
Earth-orbiting space station as a transportation center for
spacecraft traveling to and from Mars.
   Nevertheless, he estimated that the project would still
cost hundreds of billions of dollars. The White House study
didn't contain any cost estimates, but Mr. Stafford said the
group didn't expect any "blank check" to fund the proposals.
   The White House study said nuclear-powered craft could
reduce the round-trip travel time to Mars to about 320 days
from 400 days, reducing the debilitating effects on
astronauts of weightlessness and space radiation. In
addition, the powerful nuclear craft could lug more cargo
than similarly sized chemical rockets.
   Nuclear-thermal rockets heat low-weight propellant,
usually hydrogen, to high temperatures, and they produce
thrust in much the same way as conventional rockets. The
spacecraft envisioned by the study would use large,
conventional rockets to lift off from Earth and a nuclear
upper-stage for propulsion from Earth-orbit to Mars. Upon
returning from Mars, the crew would jettison the nuclear
stage into a solar orbit before the crew capsule landed on
Earth. For moon trips, nuclear rockets wouldn't be needed.
   The study "will set a path for the permanent manned
exploration of space," said Vice President Quayle. But so far
Congress has cut nearly all funds for manned expeditions, and
the panel's strong endorsement of nuclear power is certain to
raise objections from environmentalists. When NASA canceled
its last big nuclear rocket project in 1972, it had
field-tested a reactor on the ground, but had never flown one
in space.
